<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-56340" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://justice-everywhere.org/general/funding-research-randomly/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">When it comes to selecting research projects to fund, there’s a better way than peer review</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; just rule out the obviously bad or unqualified and then select the winners randomly from the rest, argues Louis Larue</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-56309" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://openquestionsblog.substack.com/p/its-a-girl-thank-god" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“I’m just arguing that it’s better to have a daughter than a son.” Just.</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Victor Kumar makes a case</span></li>
